description:
A mass shooting at Bondi Beach in the Australian city of Sydney has killed at least 11 people and wounded 29, including two police officers, police say.
One man believed to be one of the shooters has also been killed, while a second alleged shooter is in critical condition. Authorities designate the shooting a “terrorist” incident, saying it was “designed to target Sydney’s Jewish community on the first day of Hanukkah”.
Video shows a man, identified as “hero” shop owner Ahmed al Ahmed, disarming one of the attackers.
Hundreds of people had gathered at the beach for an event called Chanukah by the Sea, which was celebrating the start of the Jewish festival.
Prime Minister Anthony Albanese condemned the “targeted” attack, saying the evil that was unleashed was “beyond comprehension.”

Al Jazeera’s Danielle Robertson reports from the scene in Sydney.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Fighting along the Thailand–Cambodia border has left Thai villages near the frontier badly damaged and largely deserted.
Residents describe frequent Cambodian rocket fire, which they say is inaccurate but frightening and relentless.
Thai artillery responds throughout the day, while civilians shelter in bunkers amid ongoing shelling.
One villager was killed by shrapnel while trying to reach safety, with locals saying there was no warning.
The violence has forced communities to flee repeatedly as attacks resume with little notice.
The clashes are rooted in a long-running territorial dispute centred on the Preah Vihear temple.
That dispute has militarised the border since 2008 and has now escalated into renewed warfare.

Al Jazeera’s Jack Barton reports from Sisak Province, Thailand.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
In Cox's Bazar, Bangladesh, home to the world's largest refugee camp, education for nearly 300,000 Rohingya children has been disrupted as international aid cuts force schools to close. However, digital learning offers a ray of hope. Portable projectors bring lessons to life in cramped shelters, transforming Myanmar’s curriculum into engaging videos that help students understand and thrive. Attendance in these video-led classes remains high, with over 90 percent of children participating despite the challenges.
A unique initiative, supported by international charity Children on the Edge and local NGO Mukti, enables Rohingya teachers to deliver lessons in their own language, using cartoons, stories, and interactive methods tailored to their needs. Projects like Moja Kids, a digital newsletter filmed by students, allow children to share their voices with peers across the camp and beyond, fostering creativity and connection. author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Police in Australia say two people are in custody after a shooting was reported at Bondi Beach.
Several people are reported to have been injured in the popular tourist area just outside of Sydney.
Police have confirmed they're responding to a “serious incident” along the beach and are calling for people to take shelter.
Australia's Prime Minister's office says they're aware of the situation and urge people to follow police instructions.
Shots were reportedly fired near Campbell Parade - it's a street running along the beach. 
Police are asking people to avoid the area.

Al Jazeera’s Danielle Robertson is monitoring the latest developments.

The intention was to ensure equality among Bosnia's main ethnic groups: Bosniaks, Croats, and Serbs.
Instead, it deepened segregation and schoolchildren are taught about the divisions. 

Al Jazeera’s Rory Challands reports from Stolac in Bosnia-Herzegovina.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Officials in Gaza say at least 500 buildings, already weakened by Israel’s two-year-long war, are now at risk of collapsing because of a powerful storm.
Heavy rain and strong winds have brought down at least a dozen buildings in the Strip so far. 
The storm has made conditions worse for many families who have already been displaced more than once. 
Some Palestinians have no choice but to remain in unstable buildings, as ongoing restrictions by Israel continue to prevent access to necessary supplies and alternative shelter.
At least 14 have died, and dozens more are missing after the storm hit on Thursday. 
Authorities say they have received more than 4,300 distress calls since the storm began. 

Al Jazeera’s Hani Mahmoud has the latest from Gaza City, Palestine. 

Renald Menard is with Doctors Without Borders and based in Gaza City. 
He explains how the storm has worsened the already dire situation in the Strip.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
The US president is calling on Thailand and Cambodia to honour agreements they made over their disputed border.
But Thailand says its military will continue fighting until it faces “no further threat”.
33 people have been killed on both sides, mostly civilians, in the past week.
More than half a million people have fled to evacuation camps. 
Thailand's foreign minister says that Trump's claim fighting was coming to an end was not based on fact. 

Al Jazeera’s Jack Barton has the latest from Sisaket province in Thailand, near the border with Cambodia. 
He's in Ban Nong Mek - a village that was hit just hours ago.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
President Donald Trump says the US will retaliate after two American soldiers and a civilian interpreter were killed in Syria.
It happened near Palmyra in the central Homs region.
Syrian security forces and US troops came under fire during a joint patrol.
Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth says “partner forces” killed the assailant.
Syria's interior ministry says he had no rank within government security forces. 
An investigation is underway to determine whether the attacker was linked to ISIL.
But Donald Trump says he believes the group is responsible.

Myles Caggins is a retired US Army Colonel and former Spokesperson for the Coalition to Defeat ISIS in Iraq and Syria.
He says the US and the Syrian government continue to cooperate to combat ISIL.
